Russian Communism Is Back
Moscow—More than a year ago, I returned to my hometown of Moscow during a sabbatical from my teaching job at an American university.
My destination was not a bastion of free speech.
But there was still some freedom in this place once upon a time.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny had traveled the country trying to win support for politicians not under Kremlin control.
Protests have erupted among the populace.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate within the country.
Journalists and analysts do not always follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communists are widely seen as a relic of the past.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and his protest movement has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was dissolved for extremism, and its members are either being exiled or investigated.
Nearly every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the "foreign agent" list — worse yet — and are declared "undesirable."
Last year, Russia slipped into a non-free state, though not far and certainly not lightly.
For example, in 2012, legislation was passed to designate foreign agents, aimed at undermining or discrediting entities or individuals engaged in "political activities" and receiving funds from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, with now even retweeting becoming grounds for being labeled a foreign agent.
( "Undesirable" label will lead to complete banishment.)
Just this year, 101 new entities were added to the foreign agent list, setting a record.
A total of 359, including 88 media-related institutions and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But the core goal of journalism and propaganda is naturally to influence politics.
And that is precisely the problem: despite President Vladimir Putin positioning himself to continue controlling Russian politics for the foreseeable future, he views criticism as an existential threat.
Despite all this silence and persecution, it is a highly unlikely group—the Communist Party—that has survived and become the only genuine opposition to the Kremlin.
This is largely due to Navalny’s “Smart Vote” strategy — encouraging people to support candidates most likely to defeat the Kremlin-backed candidates — which saw the Communists perform strongly in last month’s parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the vote in the State Duma (parliament), while the pro-Kremlin United Russia party garnered nearly 49.8%.
But the Communists refuse to accept this result, insisting that the voting was manipulated.
Fact is, some experts estimated they should have garnered around 30% of the vote, versus about 35% for United Russia.
To many Russians, the Communists now seem more respectable than Putin.
But they are no longer the Communists of old.
Far from denying earthly pleasures, party members wear fur coats, travel overseas enthusiastically, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some are millionaires – such as the charming agricultural chief Pavel Grudinin (who is banned from participating in last month's elections).
Although the party is still led by the 77-year-old Gennady Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by young members.
Take Nikolai Bondarchuk, for example.
Bondarchuk, who goes by the nickname "Red Navalny," is 36 years old and severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform in 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister suggested Russians could "eat better" on a monthly salary of just 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarchuk recorded his efforts to prove him wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite threats to ban his candidacy, Bondarchuk was still allowed to participate in the parliamentary election held last month.
Although he received support from Navalny's Smart Vote system, he still lost to the United Russia Party candidate.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently proposed a slogan for a protest, accusing United Russia of being "taken over by the state and government."
There is also Anastasia Yudsova, who is 43 years old.
Like Bondarchuk, she inexplicably lost the last election.
But she remains very — and increasingly — popular.
Thanks to the Smart Vote system, another rising star, the elegant Ekaterina Engelicheva, was elected to the Moscow city duma in 2019.
Ironically, the Communist Party's modernization reflects a longing for the past: In 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and while the nation they envisioned was strict, it was not without fairness and compassion.
Like the liberal Navalny, today's Communists represent a predictable and consistent vision where one person's whims do not affect everyone else.
It is precisely this logic that has led to growing alliances among all opponents of the Kremlin: forming a united front against United Russia, the party of Putin.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as the Czech Donald Trump — failed to remain prime minister, as opposition alliances put aside their ideological differences and formed a common bloc, with its leader Petr Fiala likely to lead a new government alongside another opposition alliance.
As Fiala put it, "People have had enough of populists; they want normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also present a unified electoral list and a single candidate for prime minister in next year's parliamentary elections.
Naturally, the Czech Republic still has a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Overthrowing Putin, however, will be much harder, and we can expect further comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the Communists.
But these actions also pose risks to the Kremlin.
Now, the president claims that Russian democracy "is not dead" and points to "a vibrant opposition" as evidence, indicating that he at least still has an interest in pretending that Russia has not been pushed towards near-totalitarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But his regime is pushing Russia towards more tumultuous times.
If the Kremlin treats the Communists as it does the Russian liberal opposition, making and unmaking rules arbitrarily to drive them underground, a societal explosion becomes more likely.
And if it decides to stop suppressing them, Russian communists — yes, communists — could become an不可忽视的力量。
